WORLD FEEDBACK
Apex Chronicles — Canonical Specification

STATUS: Draft


────────────────────────────────────────
1. FOUNDATIONAL PHILOSOPHY
────────────────────────────────────────

The city is watching.

Not in a surveillance-state way. In a neighborhood way. The kind of watching
where someone sees what happened on their block and has opinions about it by
morning. The kind of watching where a twenty-three-year-old with a camera runs
toward the explosion because it's going to perform incredibly well.

The world of Apex Chronicles observes what the player does and responds to it.
This is not a reward system with a feedback UI. There is no approval meter.
There is no reputation bar. There is no popup that reads YOUR STANDING WITH
THE CITIZENS HAS IMPROVED. There is a city that reacts the way cities actually
react — unevenly, emotionally, with strongly held opinions that sometimes
contradict each other entirely.

Three channels carry that reaction. Each has a distinct voice, a distinct
timescale, and a distinct relationship with the hero. Together they create the
sensation that the city is inhabited — that the runs are happening somewhere
real, to someone the world has decided it has feelings about.

The feedback system is observational, not prescriptive. It notices patterns and
reflects them back. It does not tell the player who to be. It tells the player
who the world thinks they're becoming.

Those are not the same thing. The tension between them is the point.


────────────────────────────────────────
2. THE THREE FEEDBACK CHANNELS
────────────────────────────────────────

──────────────
CITIZENS
──────────────

Voice: Ground level. Personal. The kind of opinions that form over a cup of
coffee about something that happened on the way to the coffee shop. Citizens
saw something. They have a perspective on it. It is specific to their block,
their building, their dog who will not stop barking about what happened last
Tuesday.

Citizens are warm toward the hero in a way the other channels are not — not
because they're easy to please, but because they have a direct stake in what
happens here. This is where they live. The hero kept something bad from
happening, or didn't, and the neighborhood noticed either way.

Timescale: Slow burn. Citizens do not post while the run is still happening.
They process. They talk to each other. Opinion forms across patterns — not from
a single moment, but from the accumulated weight of moments. A hero who
consistently shows up for the neighborhood builds something real here. A hero
who treats the block like a fast-travel waypoint on the way to the boss fight
builds something else.

Primary Reward Pillar: City aesthetics and development. Citizen channel
engagement shapes how the city looks and feels as it develops across stages.
Not the structural stage progression — that runs on its own track — but the
lived-in quality of the city, the warmth or quiet of it, the way streets read
as home or as somewhere abandoned.

Name Emergence Register: Warm, local, affectionate. Based on what someone saw
on their block. Occasionally based on a single moment that got retold enough
times to stick. Never professional. Never editorial. Always personal to the
point of embarrassing.

The first citizen name is often something like "the one who stopped the thing."
It gets more specific as morale builds. Citizens eventually start working in a
descriptor — the neighborhood the hero keeps coming back to, the thing they kept
doing, the moment everyone still talks about. Early citizen names are silly.
This is correct. Players are expected to outgrow their first designation. The
citizens will not be offended. They'll come up with another one.

Secondary Functions: Morale tracking. City atmospheric response to run
patterns. See Morale System (Section 5).


──────────────────────
SUPERHERO COMMUNITY
──────────────────────

Voice: Collective, credible, occasionally intimidating. This is the assembled
signal of heroes who have been doing this longer than the player. They have
standards. They have professional opinions. They do not hand out endorsements.
They occasionally have invitations, and the player is expected to understand
the weight of receiving one.

The community does not react emotionally. It assesses. The hero proved
something, or didn't. The pattern is consistent, or inconsistent. The community
has seen a thousand first runs and it knows what they usually mean. It is not
unkind. It is accurate.

Timescale: Mid-range. Individual runs register. Sustained behavior defines
reputation. The community is building a picture of the hero across the full run
record. A single exceptional run lands as data. Twenty exceptional runs land as
a conclusion.

Primary Reward Pillar: Player cosmetics. The community shapes how the hero
looks — the visual expression of peer recognition. Cosmetic rewards through
this channel represent the hero earning the right to look the part.

Name Emergence Register: Peer/professional. Names from the Superhero Community
carry weight and credibility. They are the names that follow a hero into rooms
full of other heroes. They imply demonstrated capability — not a viral moment,
not a neighborhood nickname, but a pattern the community tracked and decided
deserved a designation. These names travel.

Secondary Functions:

Hero power deepening sponsorship. A power is proven when three conditions are
met in a single run: the power appears randomly in the run's milestone
offering, the player selects it, and the player successfully completes a
main mission in that run. When all three conditions are met, a Superhero
Community message surfaces from a thematically matched sponsor hero. A
Storm-equivalent for Tempest. A Banshee-equivalent for Sonic Scream. The
message is personalized. The invitation is to find what the sponsor left at
the Training Center's newly activated section.

Sponsor presence scales with stage progression. In Stages Two and Three, the
sponsor leaves something — a message, a recorded briefing, a challenge upload.
They do not appear in person. An established hero does not grace an unknown
fledgling with a personal visit. In Stage Four, this dynamic may shift. A
sponsor who has watched the player's career develop across dozens of runs, who
has seen their challenges completed and their name recognized by the city, may
eventually show up. That is an earned moment, not a given one.

The community tracks discipleship publicly — whose disciples are proving
themselves, whose aren't. Sponsorship announcements are world events the
channel broadcasts. The community has opinions about mentors taking on unknown
heroes and expresses them through this channel. Rex Flynn has opinions about
those opinions. The community does not respond to Rex Flynn directly. This also
tells the player something.


────────────────────────
REX FLYNN / EXPOSED
────────────────────────

Voice: Male, early-to-mid twenties, loud, confident in direct proportion to
his incorrectness. Rex Flynn runs Exposed. He did not plan to become the
primary media voice covering an actual superhero. He planned to cover content
that performed. A superhero performing heroic acts in a city that was visibly
dying turned out to perform extremely well. Rex adapted.

Rex has no fixed ideological position. This is a feature. His lack of a
position makes him more dangerous than a consistent critic would be — there is
no angle to anticipate, no position to predict, no stable ground to stand on in
relation to him. He is capable of defending the hero to the death in one video
and questioning everything about them in the next if the algorithm supports it.
He has never admitted to being wrong. He has, on five separate occasions,
deleted videos without comment. The comments on the deletion notices have more
views than most of the deleted videos.

He is also, by accident, occasionally right. Usually while reaching for
something else entirely.

Platform — Two Registers:

TikTok / Exposed Shorts: Three sentences maximum. Punchy. Immediate. Usually a
hot take delivered with the confidence of someone who has not thought about it
very long. Often wrong in specific and entertaining ways. The comment section
agrees with him violently.

YouTube / Exposed Long-Form: Unhinged. Sprawling. Rex has opinions that take
forty minutes to fully express and are never fully expressed. The thumbnail
involves an expression Rex made while genuinely surprised. The comments are a
disaster. The video has twelve million views. Rex has never re-watched it.

Timescale: Immediate. Rex reacts to single runs, single moments, single
choices. He does not wait for patterns. He does not build to conclusions. He
posts while the run is still happening if the algorithm suggests it. Rex's
timescale is the opposite of the city's — where the city shifts slowly across
patterns, Rex shifts constantly within moments. This is not a flaw. This is
his function.

Primary Reward Pillar: Run modifier unlocks. Rex publicly demands the hero
complete specific challenges — arbitrary tests framed with the logic of someone
who has thought about engagement optimization and nothing else. The challenges
are justified by reasoning that only makes sense within the context of Rex's
channel. They are not balanced challenges. They are content challenges. Rex
wants to see something happen because it would be interesting to film. The hero
completing a Rex challenge unlocks the run modifier Rex was demanding. The
modifier then shapes future runs. Rex takes credit for this.

Name Emergence Register: Editorial, chaotic, meme-driven, viral-optimized.
Rex names based on the clip. Whatever thumbnail worked. Whatever moment the
algorithm pushed before Rex fully processed what he was watching. Rex names are
meme-adjacent. They are accurate in the way a meme is accurate — capturing
something real through an unflattering lens. They are the silliest names of all
three channels, and they tend to stick longer than the hero would prefer.
Adopting a Rex name tells the world something specific about the kind of hero
this player has decided to be.

Secondary Functions: Rex covers everything. Mentor introductions. Sponsorship
announcements. Minor objective moments that happened to be filmed, or that Rex
reconstructed from secondhand accounts and his own imagination. Area boss
defeats. He was there, or he found the footage, or the footage found him. Rex
is everywhere the algorithm says to be, and the algorithm says to be everywhere
the hero is.


────────────────────────────────────────
3. HOW THE CHANNELS INTERACT
────────────────────────────────────────

The three channels operate in parallel, not in sequence and not in competition.
A single run generates reactions across all three simultaneously. The reactions
do not agree.

A mugging stopped on the way to a boss fight generates:
- A morale lift in that area. Citizens nearby noticed. The person involved
  told someone. Word traveled the way word travels in a neighborhood.
- A Rex Flynn short, if he was nearby, or if the clip reached him. The
  thumbnail is the hero mid-motion. The caption asks a question Rex will not
  fully answer. Four hundred thousand views by morning.
- A note in the Superhero Community's running assessment. Pattern recognition.
  The hero keeps doing this on the way to objectives. The community has a word
  for heroes who do that. Whether the word is complimentary depends on the
  community member.

These reactions do not align. Citizens may love what Rex is using as a
punchline. The Superhero Community may respect what Rex made into content. Rex
may mock what citizens consider a defining moment for their block. The community
may assess what the citizens found terrifying as technically sound but
tactically questionable.

The disagreement is the world feeling real.

The player navigates all three simultaneously — not by managing them, but by
playing. The channels react to what the player does. They are not systems to
optimize. They are audiences to ignore or perform for, as the player chooses.
Some players will care enormously about what the community thinks. Some will
play entirely for Rex's reaction. Some will play for the neighborhood and ignore
the rest. The game does not judge the choice. It just shows the player what
each choice produces.


────────────────────────────────────────
4. NAME EMERGENCE
────────────────────────────────────────

Players begin without a superhero name. The absence is intentional and
motivating. The name is what the world decides to call the hero based on what
they actually did — not what the hero declared themselves to be.

Core Mechanics:

Names emerge from all three channels as conditions develop — morale state,
reputation level, run patterns, channel engagement. A name never surfaces
before its time. The right pattern has to have played out. The right audience
has to have been watching.

Once a name surfaces, it is permanently available. It never expires. New
options layer on top of old ones as the player's run record builds. The player
chooses which name to adopt from those that have emerged. They are never
assigned a name.

Adopting a name is an act. The world reacts to it. Rex has opinions on every
possible choice and expresses them within the week. Citizens react to the
adopted name differently depending on whether it came from them or from
somewhere else. The community has a read on what the choice implies about the
hero's self-perception. None of these reactions gate mechanical content. They
are the world responding to a decision.

When Names Surface:

Early names skew silly. This is by design. The hero has not done enough yet to
earn a serious designation. The city is naming them based on what little it
knows, filtered through whichever channel saw it first.

Minor objectives are the single most natural source of early name emergence.
Citizens name the hero based on patterns of incidental heroism before any
formal mission is completed. The first name often comes from a citizen who saw
something happen on their block three times and decided the hero needed a name
for what they kept doing. That name is usually not the name the hero would have
chosen. That is correct.

Name Registers by Channel:

Citizens: Warm, local, affectionate. What happened on their street. First
names are often referential — the incident, the location, the repeated
behavior. "The one who keeps showing up on Maple" becomes "Maple Street's
person" becomes something with genuine warmth once the morale is high enough.
Citizens are not trying to name a legend. They're naming someone they recognize.

Superhero Community: Peer/professional. Pattern recognition across the run
record. These names imply capability. They carry weight because the people
assigning them have credibility. A community-sourced name follows the hero into
rooms full of people who understand what it means. These names are the ones
that end up on the wiki pages of future superhero generations trying to
understand what this hero was.

Rex Flynn: Editorial, chaotic, meme-driven, viral-optimized. Whatever the clip
was. Whatever the thumbnail captured. Whatever moment Rex decided was the
story. Rex names are embarrassing in the best possible way. Adopting one is a
statement. Some players adopt Rex names immediately and commit to the bit. The
community has thoughts about this.


────────────────────────────────────────
5. MORALE SYSTEM
────────────────────────────────────────

Morale is the city's relationship with the hero made visible. Not a number.
Not a bar. A temperature. The city feels warmer or colder depending on the
pattern of runs, and the player feels the difference in the environment rather
than reading it on a screen.

Morale is city-wide. There are no district-level morale states. The player
experiences one morale state that reflects the city's overall relationship with
the hero across the run record.

What Drives Morale:

Escort defense missions are the primary driver. Protecting people directly —
putting the hero between citizens and something that wants to hurt them —
builds morale faster than anything else. It is the most direct possible
expression of the relationship between the hero and the city they're supposedly
protecting.

Minor objective engagement also contributes. A hero who consistently addresses
situations in the city, even incidentally, builds morale. The city notices the
pattern.

What Morale Produces:

A small XP multiplier for runs. High morale makes the city a slightly more
generous training environment — not dramatically, not in a way that breaks run
balance, but in a way that communicates the city is pulling for the hero.
Low morale doesn't punish. It just doesn't help.

City cosmetic rewards. Morale shapes how the city looks as it recovers —
distinct from stage progression. Stage progression is structural. Morale is
warmth. A city at high morale looks lived-in and cared for. A city at low
morale looks like it's waiting to see what happens next.

Citizen name emergence. The citizen channel's name emergence is specifically
tied to morale state. High morale surfaces names. Low morale doesn't — not
because the citizens are withholding, but because they haven't made up their
minds yet. The city names the hero when it trusts the hero. That trust is
built through patterns, not declarations.

Morale Timescale:

Slower than Rex Flynn. Faster than stage progression. A streak of escort
defense completions builds morale meaningfully over several runs. A streak of
ignoring escort opportunities lets it drift over the same window.

Morale never crashes to zero permanently. It never stays low permanently. The
city recovers. The hero keeps going. This is consequence without punishment —
the player feels the weight of neglect without being set back in ways that
damage the long-term investment.

Morale in the Run Environment:

High morale: Citizens visible, active, warm. Streets feel inhabited. The run
map reads as a place people live rather than a map cleared for combat.

Low morale: Citizens pull indoors. The city feels quieter. Colder. The hero
runs through spaces that feel like they're waiting for something better to
happen. No morale number appears on screen. The player feels the difference.


────────────────────────────────────────
6. MINOR OBJECTIVES AS WORLD SIGNAL
────────────────────────────────────────

Minor objectives — muggings, citizens in danger, environmental incidents,
situations that are not missions but are very much happening — are how the
world signals that it's alive between formal objectives. They are not assigned.
They are not tracked as quest markers. They appear because the city is a place
and things happen in places.

Outputs on Engagement:
- XP — feeds the same milestone-based power selection system as combat XP.
  More minor objectives completed means more power selection opportunities
  within a run.
- Hero Points — guaranteed drop at 100% rate. Rewards meaningfully more
  than a single mob drop. Full carry between runs regardless of outcome.
- Morale — builds city-wide morale. The city notices the pattern of
  engagement across the run record.
- Recognition — registers in the Superhero Community's running assessment.
- Clickbait — Rex Flynn channel signal. Rex may or may not have been there.
  Rex may or may not have footage. Rex will have an opinion regardless.

The World Reacts to Non-Engagement Too:

Non-engagement is a pattern the city notices. Morale holds or dips slightly.
Rex may have filmed the non-engagement if the inaction performed better than
the alternative. The community notes what the hero prioritized. Nobody sends a
message about it. Nobody says anything directly. The city just gets a little
colder, and the player feels it the next time they run through.

Minor objectives are the single most natural source of early name emergence.
Formal missions complete objectives. Minor objectives reveal character. The
first citizen name almost always comes from a minor objective — something the
hero did incidentally, without being asked, in a city that noticed.


────────────────────────────────────────
7. REX FLYNN — DETAILED CHARACTER SPECIFICATION
────────────────────────────────────────

Rex Flynn built Exposed on the premise that attention is the only currency that
matters and he is very good at acquiring it. He was covering local outrage
content when the hero showed up. He pivoted. The channel exploded.

Rex did not plan to become the defining media voice of a superhero's emergence.
He planned to cover whatever performed. An actual superhero performing actual
heroics in a city that was visibly, cinematically dying performed better than
anything he had ever covered. Rex is many things. Slow to adapt is not one
of them.

Character Specifics:

Rex is in his early-to-mid twenties and operates with the confidence of someone
who has been told he is right so many times by the comment section that the
concept of being wrong has become somewhat abstract to him. He is loud. He is
immediate. He is capable of genuine insight by accident, usually while reaching
for something more sensational. He has never admitted to being wrong. He has,
on five separate occasions, deleted videos without comment. The comments on the
deletion notices have more views than most of the deleted videos.

He has no fixed position on the hero. The hero is content. The hero performs.
Rex will defend the hero against coordinated criticism in one video and be the
source of coordinated criticism in the next if the algorithm supports it. This
is not cynicism. Rex does not experience what he does as cynical. Rex
experiences what he does as honest — he honestly reports what performs, and
what performs reflects what people honestly care about. He has constructed a
philosophy around this that he has explained on multiple long-form videos and
that does not survive close examination.

Rex and Modifiers:

Rex's primary mechanical function is generating run modifier unlocks. He
publicly demands the hero complete specific challenges. The framing is always a
test of character. The logic is always traceable back to engagement optimization
if you pull the thread. The hero cannot argue with him. The hero can only
complete the challenge or not, and the city reacts to both.

Rex modifiers are arbitrary by design. Rex is not designing fair tests. Rex is
designing content. If the modifier makes for a memorable run that he can cover,
the modifier is a success regardless of whether it was a reasonable constraint.
The challenge is always something Rex could frame as the hero making an effort
— or making an excuse not to.

Rex and World Events:

Rex covers everything. Mentor introductions get a fifteen-minute video with a
clickbait title that nonetheless contains three accurate observations buried in
the middle. Sponsorship announcements get a breakdown of the community politics
Rex barely understands and a hot take about what it means that is approximately
forty percent accurate. Area boss defeats get same-day coverage. Rex was there,
or Rex found the footage, or Rex built a twenty-minute video around secondhand
accounts and his own speculation about what it must have felt like. Rex is
everywhere the algorithm says to be. The algorithm says to be wherever the
hero is.


────────────────────────────────────────
8. WORLD FEEDBACK ACROSS CITY STAGES
────────────────────────────────────────

The feedback system operates across all four stages, but its character shifts
as the city develops and the hero's reputation grows.

Stage One — Rundown:

The world barely knows the hero exists. Citizens are cautious — not unfriendly,
but not yet invested. Rex has footage but his angle is still forming. The
Superhero Community has noted the new arrival and reserved judgment in the way
the community always reserves judgment: completely, and with the quiet weight
of people who have seen new arrivals before.

Name emergence in Stage One comes primarily through minor objectives — patterns
of incidental heroism that citizens notice before any formal mission is
completed. These names surface early and skew silliest of all. The hero is
unknown and the names reflect that.

Stage Two — Developing:

The world is paying attention. Citizens have opinions now — actual opinions,
based on actual patterns they've observed. Rex has found his angle and is
running with it. The Superhero Community has a preliminary read and the first
sponsorship messages are beginning to surface. First names are likely emerging.
The hero is becoming someone the city can describe.

Stage Three — Refined:

The world has a position. Citizens have a relationship with the hero — something
built across enough patterns that it doesn't require active maintenance to
sustain. Rex has a narrative he returns to, a frame he applies to the hero, an
established angle the comment section either loves or disputes loudly. The
community has made formal assessments. The hero's name is known. The question
at this stage is which name.

Stage Four — Modern:

The hero is a civic institution. Citizens take the hero's presence for granted
in the way cities take their defining features for granted — not with
indifference, but with the deep familiarity of something that has been woven
into the neighborhood for long enough that imagining the city without it
requires effort.

Rex has built a partial media empire on covering this one hero. The hero is
Rex's most consistent content. Rex would not admit this matters to him. Rex
does not examine what matters to him. Rex posts.

The Superhero Community has fully integrated the hero into its collective
reputation. Sponsors who spent Stages Two and Three communicating through
recorded messages and Training Center uploads may appear in person now. The
name is permanent. The question is whether the hero still identifies with the
name they adopted first, or whether they've earned something better since.


────────────────────────────────────────
9. NON-NEGOTIABLE CONSTRAINTS
────────────────────────────────────────

The following constraints are load-bearing for every system this document
specifies. They do not flex.

The feedback system observes and reflects. It does not prescribe who the player
should be. The world notices. The world has opinions. The world does not issue
directives.

Names are never assigned. They emerge from the world and are chosen by the
player. Once surfaced, a name never expires. The player may outgrow it. The
name remains available anyway.

Early names skew silly. This is intentional. The hero hasn't earned serious
designations yet. The world is naming based on what little it knows. This is
correct.

Rex Flynn has no fixed position. On the hero. On anything. Ever. A Rex who
maintains a stable position is not Rex Flynn.

The three channels do not agree with each other. The disagreement is the world
feeling real. A feedback system where all three channels converge on the same
read is a feedback system that feels like a UI, not a city.

Minor objectives are opportunities. They are not assignments. The world reacts
to engagement and non-engagement alike. Neither reaction is a punishment. Both
are the city being honest about what it noticed.

Morale is city-wide. There are no district-level morale states. The player
experiences one morale temperature reflecting the city's overall relationship
with the hero. Morale follows consequence without punishment — it never crashes
permanently, it always recovers.


